1 Task 1: Data Source

The source of data for this project is the National Health and Nutrition Survey (NHANES) database. I will specifically be using data from the 2013 - 2014 survey.

NHANES data may be found at: https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/nhanes/index.htm

Per the NHANES documentation (https://wwwn.cdc.gov/nchs/data/series/sr02_162.pdf), sampling methods utilized a complex, multistage probability sampling design in order to identify a population representative of the civilian, non-institutionalized US population. Upon agreement to participate in the study, study staff performed in-home screening, interviews, laboratory collection, and physical examination. More detailed methods are described below.

Specification of the people and methods involved:

According to the NHANES Sample Design document for 2011-2014 (see link above), as of 1999, NHANES became a continuous survey of non-institutionalized, civilian residents residing in the 50 states and the District of Columbia. NHANES utilizes a “complex, multistage probability sampling design” with sample selection occurring in stages, in a specific order:

  1. Selection of primary sampling units (PSUs), (counties or groups of counties)

  2. Selection of clusters of households within PSUs

  3. Selection of specific households within clusters

  4. Selection of individuals within households

Once selected, households were sent a letter introducing NHANES and explaining the selection process and the study overview. Field Interviewers approached selected households in person to “screen” participants, a process which collected sex, age, race, and ethnicity data to determine eligibility. Based on the information collected, a computer algorithm determined whether or not any (or all) individuals in the household would be selected to participate.

Approximately 12,000 individuals per year were planned for selected for potential participation. In the 2013-2014 survey year, approximately 30 counties out of 3,000 counties in the US were selected as PSUs. The subsequent “Screened Sample” consisted of 14,332 out of a potential 311,204,216 individuals in the targeted PSUs. Of those, 10,175 were interviewed (71.0% response rate) and 9,813 were examined (68.5% response rate).

NHANES uses an approach which combines personal interviews and standardized physical examinations. The interviews occur either in the participant’s home or in a Mobile Examination Center (MEC). The data were collected throughout the target year, through a series PSU-specific site visits held at temporary NHANES field offices. If selected, potential participants signed a consent form for participation in the home interview process. If they agreed to participate, a “Relationship Questionnaire” and a “Family Questionnaire” were completed and, for households with a participant over the age of 12, a sample of water was collected. Additional testing and examinations were conducted at NHANES field offices.

A MEC was identified for each field office and trained study personnel were brought in for the visit. The physical examination and sample collection for laboratory testing occurred in the MEC. Study personnel guided participants through the informed consent process, collected all data and samples, and performed all examinations. Study personnel included a MEC manager, a coordinator, a physician, two health interviewers, two dietary interviewers, four health technologists, three medical technologists, and a phlebotomist. The initial interview was administered by trained Household Interviewers in the participant’s home. Rarely, these occurred outside the home, in a field office or public place.

For the 2013-2014 survey, there were no age restrictions imposed for inclusion. Potential participants were excluded if they met any of the following criteria:

  1. In supervised care or custody in an institutional setting

  2. Active-duty military personnel

  3. Family members of active-duty personnel, living overseas

  4. Any individual residing outside the 50 US states and District of Columbia

Based on our research question and the predictor and outcome availability, our study will include all men and women above the age of 40 years enrolled in NHANES during the 2013-2014 survey year.

2.0.1 Summary of dataset tidy process

In order to start to construct my tidy dataset, I first downloaded the pertinent datasets from the NHANES database. These were converted outside of R from XPT files to CSV files using SAS Universal Viewer. The CSV files were read into R using the read.csv function. Once the CSV files were loaded, the variables of choice from each dataset were selected, including the subject ID “SEQN” which served as a link between the datasets. The datasets were merged in a stepwise fashion to create a single large dataset. In each step, 2 datasets were merged and then the observations without complete data were removed from the merged dataset using the complete.cases function. This was performed in a stepwise fashion to prevent R from crashing through the merging process.

Once the dataset was complete, non-informative data was filtered out so that all observations were both complete and contained useful data. Data which was filtered out included place-holder data indicating “Refused to Answer” or “Do Not Know.” The variable names for the variables which would remain through to analysis were renamed to a more informative name. For example, “WHD020” was changed to “weight.” This completed the NHANES_raw dataset.

New variables created to convert a numeric outcome into a binary outcome.

  • Calculated BMI outcome: The BMI of participants was collected in the NHANES project. The variable containing the numeric values was converted into a binary variable (BMI_bin) using the BMI classification structure from the World Health Organization (http://apps.who.int/bmi/index.jsp?introPage=intro_3.html). BMI values below 25.0 were classified as Normal/under weight. BMI values at or above 25.0 were classified as Overweight/Obese. BMI_f contains the text version of the classifications.

New variables were calculated to create informative factors. The calculated variables are as follows:

  • Taste Tests: For the “taste” variable, I used two tests used in the NHANES database. The participant was given 20 mL of a 1 mM solution of quinine (which has a bitter taste) and 1 mM NaCl (which has a salty taste). The participant was to swish the sample around their whole mouth and then identify what taste it elicited, out of 4 multiple choice responses. For the calculations, each correct answer was coded with a 1, each incorrect answer was coded with a 0. The numerical variable “taste” was created by summing the two coded taste test results. The factored variable “taste_f” was also created which leveled the test results. A sum of both tests resulting in a 2 (both tests correctly identified) was coded as “Normal.” A sum of 1 (only one test correctly identified) was coded as “Borderline” and a sum of 0 (both tests incorrect) was coded as “Impaired.” The concept for using this test series is that a normal or impaired sense of taste may affect the desire a person has to consume food.

  • Smell Tests: For the “smell” variable, I used a series of 8 scent identification tests used in the NHANES project. The participant was asked to smell a scratch and sniff card and identify the specific scent, from a choice of 4 multiple choice responses. The scents were: chocolate, strawberry, soap, smoke, leather, grape, onion, and natural gas. Each correct answer was coded with a 1, each incorrect was coded as a 0. The numerical variable “smell” was created by summing the results of all 8 tests. A factored variable “smell_f” was created with the following levels: 0-2 correct = Severe impairment, 3-4 = Moderate impairment, 5-6 = Mild impairment, and 7-8, Normal, or no impairment. The concept for using this test series is that a normal or impaired sense of smell significantly affects the sense of taste and, therefore, may affect the desire a person has to consume food.

  • Food Insecurity: Participants in the NHANES project were given 3 statements regarding food insecurity. “I/We worried whether my/our food would run out before I/we got money to buy more.” “The food the I/we bought just didn’t last, and I/we didn’t have money to get more.” “I/we couldn’t afford to eat balanced meals.” The possible response options were given and each was coded by NHANES: 1 = “often true” 2 = “Sometimes true” and 3 = “Never true” The numerical variable “food” was created by summing the results of all 3 questions. A factored variable “food_f” was created with the following levels, in terms of the level of food insecurity the participant experiences: 3-4 = “severe” 5-7 = “moderate” and 8-9 = “mild/none.” The concept behind using this variable is that when people suffer from food insecurity, it might affect the amount or quality of food to which they have access, which may affect subsequent weight.

Once the new calculated variables were created, a subset of the entire dataset was taken so that only the variables needed for the later analysis would be included in the tidy dataset. This subsetting resulted in a dataset, “NHANES_tidy” containing 16 variables and 3579 complete observations. Since we are allowed a maximum of 1000 observations, a random subset of my tidy dataset were pulled into a new final tidy dataset, called “tidy1000.”

Variable Type Details
SEQN character Subject identification number
weight quantitative Self-reported weight at screening, in pounds.

5 Task 5: My Subjects

The subjects for my analysis were participants in the National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey (NHANES). The target population for NHANES is the non-institutionalized civilian resident population of the United States. There are no age restrictions for participation, but those 80 years or over are grouped together to prevent de-identification. A random selection of 1000 subjects from an initial group of 3522 were selected for these analyses.

6 Task 6: My Variables

  • SEQN: Participant identification number. This number is unique to each participant and was used to link the data across datasets within the NHANES database.

  • weight: The self-reported weight of the participant, in pounds. Collected from males and females ages 16 to 150 years.

  • bmi: Body Mass Index (BMI) of participants. Numerical value, calculated during the visit. Results in kg/m^2. Collected from males and females ages 2 to 150 years.

  • bmi_bin: A binary variable for BMI created from the variable bmi. Participants with a BMI below 25.0 were coded with a “0”. Participants with a BMI at or above 25.0 were coded with a “1”.

  • bmi_f: A factored variable with 2 levels, recoded from the variable bim_bin. Observations of “0” were coded as “Normal/Underweight” and observations of “1” were coded as “Overweight/Obese.”

  • age: Participant age, in years, at the time of screening. Collected from males and females ages 0 to 150 years.

  • sex_f: Participant’s sex. Males were coded as “1” and Females were coded as “2.” Collected from males and females ages 0 to 150 years.

  • sex_f_name: Participant’s sex. Males were coded as “1” and Females were coded as “2.” Collected from males and females ages 0 to 150 years. This variables was created by replacing the numerical “1” and “2” with “Male” and “Female” respectively.

  • health: A factored variable with 5 levels reflecting the answer to the question: “Would you say your health in general is…?” Response options included: 1=Excellent, 2=Very Good, 3=Good, 4=Fair, and 5=Poor. Collected from males and females ages 12 to 150 years.

  • oral_f: A factored variable reflecting the answer to the question “About how long has it been since you have seen a dentist?” The concept behind inclusion of this variable is that dental care is usually the the least consistently utilized form of health care. The frequency of dental care should be reflective of the level of care an individual pays to their overall health, with more recent visits likely to reflect a higher attention to general health care. Response options included: 1= 6m or less, 2= More than 6m, but not more than 1y, 3=More than 1y but not more than 2y, 4=More than 2y but not more than 3y, 5=More than 3y but not more than 5y, 6=More than 5y ago. Collected from males and females ages 1 to 150 years.

  • smoke: A quantitative laboratory measure of serum cotinine levels, in ng/mL. Cotinine levels are a measure of recent cigarette exposure, whether it is first-hand or second-hand smoke. Collected from males and females ages 3 to 150 years.

  • sleep: A quantitative variable reflecting the answer to the question: “How much sleep do you usually get at night on weekdays or workdays?” Response options were the number of hours, up to a ceiling of 12 hours. Respondents sleeping at or more than 12 hours a night were grouped together at 12 hours. Collected from males and females ages 16 to 150 years.

  • rest: A quantitative variable reflecting the answer to the question: “How much time do you usually spend sitting on a typical day?” Response options were the number of minutes. Collected from males and females ages 12 to 150 years.

  • taste: For the “taste” variable, I used two tests used in the NHANES database. The participant was given 20 mL of a 1 mM solution of quinine (which has a bitter taste) and 1 mM NaCl (which has a salty taste). The participant was to swish the sample around their whole mouth and then identify what taste it elicited, out of 4 multiple choice responses. For the calculations, each correct answer was coded with a 1, each incorrect answer was coded with a 0. The numerical variable “taste” was created by summing the two coded taste test results. The concept for using this test series is that a normal or impaired sense of taste may affect the desire a person has to consume food. Collected from males and females ages 40 to 150 years.

  • taste_f: The factored variable “taste_f” was created from the variable “taste” which leveled the results found in the variable taste. A sum of both tests resulting in a 2 (both tests correctly identified) was coded as “Normal.” A sum of 1 (only one test correctly identified) was coded as “Borderline” and a sum of 0 (both tests incorrect) was coded as “Impaired.” The concept for using this test series is that a normal or impaired sense of taste may affect the desire a person has to consume food.

  • smell: For the “smell” variable, I used a series of 8 scent identification tests used in the NHANES project. The participant was asked to smell a scratch and sniff card and identify the specific scent, from a choice of 4 multiple choice responses. The scents were: chocolate, strawberry, soap, smoke, leather, grape, onion, and natural gas. Each correct answer was coded with a 1, each incorrect was coded as a 0. The numerical variable “smell” was created by summing the results of all 8 tests. The concept for using this test series is that a normal or impaired sense of smell significantly affects the sense of taste and, therefore, may affect the desire a person has to consume food. Collected from males and females ages 40 to 150 years.

  • smell_f: A factored variable created from the variable “smell” with the following levels: 0-2 correct = Severe impairment, 3-4 = Moderate impairment, 5-6 = Mild impairment, and 7-8, Normal, or no impairment. The concept for using this test series is that a normal or impaired sense of smell significantly affects the sense of taste and, therefore, may affect the desire a person has to consume food.

  • food: Participants in the NHANES project were given 3 statements regarding food insecurity. “I/We worried whether my/our food would run out before I/we got money to buy more.” “The food the I/we bought just didn’t last, and I/we didn’t have money to get more.” “I/we couldn’t afford to eat balanced meals.” The possible response options were given and each was coded by NHANES: 1 = “often true” 2 = “Sometimes true” and 3 = “Never true” The numerical variable “food” was created by summing the results of all 3 questions. The concept behind using this variable is that when people suffer from food insecurity, it might affect the amount or quality of food to which they have access, which may affect subsequent weight. Collected from males and females ages 0 to 150 years.

  • food_f: A factored variable “food_f” was created from the variable “food” with the following levels, in terms of the level of food insecurity the participant experiences: 3-4 = “severe” 5-7 = “moderate” and 8-9 = “mild/none.” The concept behind using this variable is that when people suffer from food insecurity, it might affect the amount or quality of food to which they have access, which may affect subsequent weight.

10 Task 10 Analysis: Linear Regression

For this linear regression analysis, I will build a linear model which will predict an individual’s weight from a series of predictor variables available in the NHANES database.

The first task in preparing for the linear regression analysis is to determine the potential impact each of my potential predictors may have on my outcome of choice. To this end, I will run a Spearman Rho-squared analysis of the predictor options. I specifically included a large number of predictor options beyond the required minimum of 4.

The potential confounders, sex and age, will be included in the model regardless of how they fare in the model development. I will also need to be wary of potential collinearity between some of my predictor variables. For example, the predictor “health” is a factored variable with 5 levels reflecting the answer to the question: “Would you say your health in general is…?” Response options included: 1=Excellent, 2=Very Good, 3=Good, 4=Fair, and 5=Poor. People who are extremely over or under weight may rank their health with a worse (higher) rating–and this may be a result of weight, not a cause of it.

10.1.2 Transformation of outcome variable assessment

Since the outcome variable is not completely normal, I want to determine if a transformation might be helpful.

boxCox(lm((weight) ~ age + sex_f + health_f + oral_f + smoke + sleep + rest + taste_f + smell_f + food_f, data=tidy1000))

If the distribution of the outcome weight was normal, the BoxCox plot would have indicated that with a result of ~1. In this case, the plot indicates that a transformation may be helpful–in this case ln(x) is the transformation which is the most likely to be helpful.

I will consider transforming my outcome, weight, with a ln(x) transformation.

10.1.3 Normality assessment of transformed outcome variable

eda.1sam(dataframe=tidy1000,
         variable=log(tidy1000$weight), 
         x.title="Participant Weight (pounds)",
         ov.title="Outcome Variable Normality Assessment")

The log transformed outcome variable is MUCH more normally distributed. I will definitely use this in my model.

10.1.4 Spearman Rho-squared Plot

plot(Hmisc::spearman2(log(weight) ~ age + sex_f + health_f + oral_f + smoke + sleep + rest + taste_f + smell_f + food_f, data=tidy1000))

The Spearman Rho-squared analysis indicates that there is likely to be some predictive power in including sex (by far the strongest), rest, health, and age as predictors for weight. Behind these three strong predictors, are taste, smell, and sleep. Finally, the predictors expected to have the least predictive punch are oral, food, and smoke.

10.1.5 Matrix Analysis

In order to investigate the relationship between the variables, a Matrix Analysis will be performed. This will identify collinearity between variables, if any exists, of which I must be mindful throughout the analyses.

pairs(~ age + sex_f + health_f + oral_f + smoke + sleep + rest + taste_f + smell_f + food_f + log(weight),
      data=tidy1000,
      main = "NHANES Weight Matrix Analysis",

The matrix analysis indicates that the largest amount of collinearity exists between taste_f and smell_f, wt an R = 0.40. That is scientifically valid–as much of the sense of taste is directly related to the sense of smell. Therefore, I will only allow one of the two to be used in the final model. There is a bit of collinearity between the outcome variable and health_f (R = 0.15). This is a bit concerning, as there is a definite chance that, as discussed above, the variable may be affected by the outcome variable. This will need to be considered throughout the analysis.

10.2.1.4 Non-linearity assessment conclusions

I performed non-linearity assessments above, for the 4 variables which the Spearman Rho-squared plot indicated had the most predictive punch. I assessed the use of non-linear terms for age and rest as well as interactions between age, health, rest, and se, in pairs. From these 4 models, I have determined that of the non-linearity assessments I performed (residual plots and splines for age (mod1) and rest (mod1)and interaction pairs between age, sex, rest, and health (mods 2-4)), only one of these non-linear additions provided a significant increase in predictive power to the model. I will, therefore, only include an interaction between age and health in my models. Important note: when including this interaction in my model, the residual models including the interaction are negatively impacted by its inclusion (data not shown). The residual plot’s loess curve becomes much more curved, the Q-Q plot deviates more from linearity at the upper end of the plot, and the scale-location plot curves upward towards the upper end of the x-axis. The convergence of the negative results led me to the decision to remove the interaction term from the models.

Through these model assessments, I also gained information about the significance of variable inclusion in the models. The variables that demonstrated some significance in at least one of the models were: age, sex, health, rest, smoke, and taste. The variables that demonstrated essentially no significance in the models were: smell, oral, food, and sleep.

10.3 Best subsets analysis with ols model

I will perform a best subsets analysis to determine the best combination of remaining predictors. The selection of predictors I will include were influenced by the models viewed in the non-linearity assessments. Erring on the side of inclusion, I will use age, sex, health, rest, smoke, taste, oral, food, and sleep in my initial model.

10.4.2 Impact of individual predictors on the outcome

ggplot(Predict(mod_bs),

The graphs above detail the impact of each predictor on the outcome, log(weight). The impact is as follows:

  • age: as age increases, log(weight) decreases. The configence intervals remain fairly constant across ages.
  • health_f: Responses to the question for health_f of 0,1,2 correlate with a lower log(weight) than responses of 3,4,5. The CI for responses 2,3,4 are smaller than the other response CIs.
  • rest: As the amount of time spent at rest increases, so does the predicted weight. CIs are slightly smaller in the middle of the rest range and expand slightly at the upper end of the range.
  • sex_f: Sex = Female correlates with a lower log(weight) than does Sex = Male. CIs are uniform across this binary predictor.
  • smoke: As cotinine levels increase, log(weight) decreases. CIs increase as continine levels increase.

10.5 Comparing out of sample predictive ability of the model with cross validation

In order to test the validity of my model, I will use the Cross Validation method.

set.seed(90210)
# Setting up the cross validation--using 10-fold validation
CV_model <- tidy1000 %>%
  crossv_kfold(k = 10) %>%
  mutate(model = map(train, ~ lm(log(weight) ~ sex_f + age + health_f + rest + smoke, data = .)))

CV_predictions <- CV_model %>%
unnest(map2(model, test, ~ augment(.x, newdata = .y)))

CV_res <- CV_predictions %>%
summarize(Model = "3",
RMSE = sqrt(mean((log(weight) - .fitted) ^2)),
MAE = mean(abs(log(weight) - .fitted)))

Plotting the predictions from the cross validation process.

CV_predictions %>%
  mutate(errors = log(weight) - .fitted) %>%
  ggplot(., aes(x = errors)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, fill = "darkviolet", col = "yellow") +
  labs(title = "Cross-Validated Errors Predicting log(weight)", 
       subtitle = "Best Subsets model, tidy1000", x = "Error in predicting log(weight)")

The model appears to be reasonable prediction-wise. There is a bit of spread in the prediction error, but very few are significantly divergent from the group. The model appears to balance predictions above and below the actual values, exhibiting a fairly normal distribution around error = 0.0.

Based on the residuals versus fitted values plot above, there is not a curve evident in the loess smooth, but there do appear to be a few outliers that have higher residual values at the mid-upper range of the fitted values. The plot, however, does resemble a “fuzzy football.” Additionally the normal QQ plot demonstrates these outliers as well but overall there does not appear to be any major evidence of non-normality in our residuals. Further examination via Leverage plot does not reveal any points with Cook’s distance >0.5, but there are some points with a higher influence in the dataset; there are several so therefore these are likely to not be related to errors but actual observations that we need to be aware of in our model. A scale-location plot demonstrates overall constant variance across the range of fitted values of log(weight).

Therefore, the standard regression assumptions for residuals (Linearity, independence, constant variance, and normality) appear to be met. There is really little issue with normality given that the outcome was transformed to adjust for normality.

11 Task 11 Analysis: Logistic Regression

For this logistic regression analysis, I will build a logistic model which will predict whether a person is overweight/obese, or not, from a series of predictor variables available in the NHANES database.

The first task in preparing for the logistic regression analysis is to determine the potential impact each of my potential predictors may have on my outcome of choice. To this end, I will run a Spearman Rho-squared analysis of the predictor options. I specifically included a large number of predictor options beyond the required minimum of 4. I do not expect the confounders, age and sex, to be as much of an issue in the logistic regression, due, in part, to the nature of the outcome variable. The outcome, bmi_bin was created from the BMI measurements. BMI is less variable due to age and sex, as height is part of the calculation to determine BMI. Just in case, I will graph my outcome, accounting for age and sex.

Before deciding which predictors to use in my initial model, I want to look at the Spearman Rho-squared plot. This plot should give me an idea of the predictive power of each potential predictor.

11.1.0.1 Spearman Rho-squared Plot

plot(Hmisc::spearman2(BMI_bin ~ age + sex_f + health_f + oral_f + smoke + sleep + rest + taste_f + smell_f + food_f, data=tidy1000))

The Spearman Rho-squared plot indicates that the variables which may pack the greatest predictive punch are health and rest first, followed by oral, sleep, and food. The remaining variables may have an impact, however they are likely to make much less of a difference in the predictive power of the model. To assess non-linearity of predictors, I will focus on the two apparently most important predictors, health and rest. Health is a factor, and rest is a quantitative variable. I will include an interaction between these predictirs and a spline for rest in my initial model.

The summary of the glm model confirms what the lrm model information told told us, that the most important predictors are health, rest, and smoke.

Next, I want to examine the effect sizes for the predictors–using the lrm model.

plot(summary(lasso_lrm))

The effect sizes as shown in the plot above help us understand the significance differences across the predictors.

  • Age, sex, and sleep: For age, sex, and sleep, which are not significant contributors, they have a very narrow effect size which crosses an odds ratio of 1.0–which means no difference in odds.

  • Rest: The predictor rest, however, also has a small effect size, but it does not cross odds = 1.0, and therefore the predictor shows some significance in terms of predictive ability.

  • Smoke: The predictor smoke is significant, and the effect size is incredibly tiny–and right by odds = 1.0. For smoke, the 25-75% range is from 0.011 to 0.604. Perhaps the significance is related to the tiny effect size???

  • Health: This predictor is a multi-leveled factor. Each level has a different effect size and range at different odds ratios. There is an apparent trend that the lower scores have a lower odds ratio than the higher ones. This trend is likely responsible for the significance observed with this predictor.

  • Smell and Food: The predictors smell and food are leveled factors. Each level has a fairly large effect size, each of which cross the odds = 1.0 threshold, thus accounting for the lack of significance observed.

ggplot(Predict(lasso_lrm, fun = plogis))

The individual predictor plots also help explain the effect of each predictor on the model.

  • Age: As age increases, the odds of being overweight/obese decrease, but not a great deal.

  • Food: The odds ranges across the factor levels overlap almost completely and without a directional trend across levels, explaining the lack of significance.

  • Health: The odds ranges across the levels of this factor overlap a bit, but the trend is directional, which may contribute to the signifance observed.

  • Rest: As the amount of time a person is at rest increases, so do the odds of being overweight/obese. The slope of this trend line is reasonably steep and the confidence intervals are fairly tight.

  • Sex: The odds ranges for male and female overlap a great deal, explaining the lack of significance.

  • Sleep: As the amount of sleep an individual typically gets increases, the odds of being overweight/obese decreases slightly. The CIs also spread a bit at the upper and lower ranges. The slope is fairly flat, possibly explaining the lack of significance.

  • Smell: The odds ranges for all of the levels of this factor overlap, explaining the lack of significance for this factor in the model.

  • Smoke: As the cotinine levels increase in individuals, indicating a current smoker with increasingly heavy useage, the odds of being overweight/obese decreases. The slope of the line is fairly steep, but the CIs fan out at the upper end of the smoke level–possibly die to lower numbers of people in this range. The fairly steep slope may explain the significance of this predictor.
